This is a common issue with .NET MAUI on .NET 10. Android 15 (and MAUI .NET 10) adopted **edge-to-edge** rendering by default, which means `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` no longer works. You now need to react to **keyboard (IME) window insets** instead.

## Recommended approach

In your chat page, listen for IME insets on Android and adjust the page's bottom padding:

**1. Add a platform-specific handler in your page code-behind:**

```csharp
// ChatPage.xaml.cs
protected override void OnAppearing()
{
    base.OnAppearing();
#if ANDROID
    KeyboardInsetHelper.Attach(this);
#endif
}

protected override void OnDisappearing()
{
    base.OnDisappearing();
#if ANDROID
    KeyboardInsetHelper.Detach();
#endif
}
```

**2. Create the helper under `Platforms/Android/`:**

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/KeyboardInsetHelper.cs
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

namespace YourApp.Platforms.Android;

public static class KeyboardInsetHelper
{
    private static IDisposable? _listener;

    public static void Attach(ContentPage page)
    {
        var activity = Platform.CurrentActivity!;
        var rootView = activity.Window!.DecorView!;

        var callback = new InsetsCallback(page);
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(rootView, callback);
        _listener = callback;
    }

    public static void Detach()
    {
        _listener?.Dispose();
        _listener = null;
    }

    private sealed class InsetsCallback
        : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener, IDisposable
    {
        private readonly ContentPage _page;

        public InsetsCallback(ContentPage page) => _page = page;

        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(
            global::Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var ime = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var nav = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use whichever is larger: keyboard or nav bar
            int bottomPx = Math.Max(ime.Bottom, nav.Bottom);
            double bottomDip = bottomPx / DeviceDisplay.MainDisplayInfo.Density;

            _page.Padding = new Thickness(0, 0, 0, bottomDip);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Typical chat page layout (ChatPage.xaml):**

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
  <Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />

    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
      <Entry Placeholder="Message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
      <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
  </Grid>
</ContentPage>
```

## How it works

| Keyboard state | `ime.Bottom` | Effect |
|---|---|---|
| **Closed** | 0 | Padding falls back to nav-bar height |
| **Open** | large value | Page bottom padding pushes the `Entry` above the keyboard |

## Alternative: quick-and-dirty manifest fix

If you just want the old behavior back (less reliable on Android 15+):

```xml
<!-- Platforms/Android/AndroidManifest.xml -->
<activity android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" ... />
```

…but this is **deprecated at API 35** and may be ignored. The insets approach above is the forward-compatible solution.
